to conduct the easier enquiry whether a defendant knew the nature and
quality of his actions. If not, the defendant is to be considered
insane and there is no need to pass to the harder and broader enquiry
whether the defendant knew his actions were wrong. And, because, owing
to this sequence, the factfinder is to ask whether a defendant lacks
moral capacity only when he possesses cognitive capacity, the only
